<br>
What you know does not equal what your character knows. Players  (that's you) have to have a basic knowlege of metagame mechanics. What spells they can learn, what weapons they can use, their level, the general /con of other monsters, stats, etc...<br>
<br>
You don't have to impart that knowlege to your character. Just because you know what that odd item is for, it doesn't mean your character does. You have to know the levels of the characters you group with (important game mechanic to avoid abuse), but that doens't mean you're character knows. Role-playing is in part at least, playing your character without the metagame knowledge that you have.<br>
<br>
Back to the topic at hand, just back up and think about what your character would do. Just being 'good' doesn't mean your character is Paladin perfect. He may have some minor flaws like a bit of greed, or be dangerously naive. The world is full of basically good people who compromise what that think they should do just to put food on the table.<br>
<br>
Another point is to keep in mind, when finding group members, your character would seek out people he trusts his life with to go do something dangerous. Your character would ask questions of them, and try to get to know them. The same isn't true in a merchantile situation. Exactly how deeply would your character pry into the personal life of a potential customer? What stereo-types does your character have of certain races? Use your character's persona to determine who to trade with. Not some meta-game mechanic.<br>
