<br>
If you want to roleplay faults that are not covered by the game mechanics of whatever system you are playing, fine! Wanna play a blind character? Sure... turn off your screen! Wanna be maimed? Never equip anything on your left arm if you like. Just gotta be a traditional vampire? Go right ahead and delete yourself if you ever catch a ray of sunlight. EQ just doesn't have mechanics for that stuff. You are more than welcome to simulate them however you like, but everyone else isn't failing as roleplayers if they don't do so.<br>
<br>
Likewise, EQ includes the idea that the ability to assess items is something everyone can do. Just like everyone can, with no training whatsoever, instantly ride a horse if they buy one. Or can easily function in any sort of armor they can squeeze themselves into, with no training whatsoever. Not very realistic, eh?<br>
<br>
The point is that roleplaying does not exist independent of the rule structure of the game. In D&amp;D, you need special abilities, skills, or spells to learn what stuff does above a certain minimal level. In Asheron's Call, your chance to identify things is based on your training in that type of identification and your raw intellect. Not here - here, everyone can do it. That is the system.<br>
<br>
It isn't metagaming to use the basic, coded functions of the game - assessing items to see what they do, /conning monsters to decide whether or not to attack, etc. Every game has a few things they set by the wayside, favoring gameplay over 'realism'. In EQ, appraising items happens to be one of those things.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Ellywig</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
