Tatter Pikken, it's good to see that there are other sane people wandering this world of ours. We'll definitely have to get together for a few drinks some time. I know this Sebilisian who's one hell of a bartender...<br>
<br>
(ooc)<br>
Right, then, back to the thread at hand. It's really tricky to determine what is, or is not, IC information in the game. Obviously, things like health, mana, and stamina are (though I think saying things like &quot;60%&quot; borders on the OOC line). The effects of items you have equipped probably should be, too, though it's an open question as to how one talks about a &quot;+4 DEX&quot; item. It's stated in the EverQuest manual from Ruins of Kunark that /consider is a mystical ability that all Norrathians possess, so it's IC as well, as a convention of the game world. (I like to view it as reading the aura around the target; ergo, the /con color equates to the color of their aura.)<br>
<br>
As for items you don't have equipped, I think that really depends on your character. A grizzled old adventurer probably knows a lot about a number of pieces of equipment, while a magus of the 16th circle or later has the Identify spell and can use that as his explanation for the knowledge. Would a naive Druid fresh from the Surefall Glade be privy to such information? OOC, yes; IC, maybe not.<br>
<br>
In any event, I agree with Ellywig that this is a lot a function of how you choose to play, and that, given the complexity of the issue, it's unfair to consider those who play to a different standard &quot;wrong.&quot; <p>Illudin<br>
Enchanter and Incorrigible Adventurer<br>
"Onward, all, to our destinies! Adventure awaits!"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uayida.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ayida</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 220<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/27/02 9:26:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2204.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Is Evils trading with Goods hypocritical?</span><hr size=1> I can't believe that I'm agreeing with a) Ellywig, never mind agreeing with b) Shintou, in the same post.<br>
<br>
I tailor my RP, for consistency's sake, to take into account much of what is necessary knowledge to get by in whatever world I'm in.  <br>
<br>
Therefore, Ayida believes that  the world is broken up into &quot;zones&quot; with magical barriers between them, and can refer to them IC.  Concepts of level, hit points, and any other stat-based thing are included in that.  As you learn the game, your characters get more knowledge as well, and sometimes I'll refer to &quot;library research&quot; from 3rd Gate, or &quot;I got someone to get me a book from Erudin library&quot;, or &quot;I was talking to this dwarf and *he* told me. . ..the list is endless.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hi, I'm Ayida.  I'm in Iceclad, just zoned.  I'm a level/rank/season 52 warrioress.&quot;, is completely IC to me.  When I'm around folks who don't talk that way, or if they're always couching things like ((ooc: what's your level)), with OOC signifiers, then I'll try to adapt and use *their* habits of what makes them comfortable.  If I'm around folks who think I'm talking OOC and prefer it that way, I don't disabuse them of the notion by waving it in their face.<br>
<br>
As long as in my head, I can hear what *Ayida* thinks, and my fingers will type it out, (funny isn't it, how nearly all our communications IC *have* to be conveyed by words, one of the best RPer's on the server is Titaisia, btw, and why?  Because she communicates with her Vah Shir so effectively by using the body movements, distance, and the bare bones non-verbal clues we're given.).  If I was strongly stuck in the &quot;my character doesn't know what my player knows perspective, even the fact that we use written vs. verbal/non-verbal communication would bug me.<br>
<br>
Just a couple thoughts, tangential to the thread. . ..<br>
<br>
